  "prompt": "If I push a rod of length 0.3 million km, the other end of rod moves immediately. Would that not mean information has traveled faster than light?",
  "response": "It may seem intuitively that pushing a rod would result in instantaneous movement at the other end, but in reality, the motion propagates through the rod at a finite speed, the speed of sound in the material of the rod. This is because when you push one end, the molecules of the rod interact with each other and transmit the force along its length.\n\nEven if the rod were perfectly rigid (which no real material is), the propagation of mechanical signals (such as the compression or tension wave resulting from the push) would still be limited by the properties of the material and typically move much slower than the speed of light. Most materials have a speed of sound orders of magnitude slower than the speed of light.\n\nTherefore, the information about the push at one end of the rod does not travel faster than light; it adheres to the constraints imposed by the physical properties of the material, ensuring that no information transmission exceeds the speed of light, thereby preserving the principles of relativity.",
